Winner Take-all Network

In this project, we will cluster points located on the surface of a 3D-sphere with radius 1. Points are clustered in 3 region, and each cluster has 30 points. In other words, there are 90 points in total. The first cluster(c1) of points have (-,+,+) cordinates, the second cluster(c2) of points have (+,+,+) coordinates. Lastly, the third cluster(c3) of points have (-,-,-). All points are genereated from chisquare distribution, after producing the points, signs are adjusted as explained above. Then, data points are normalized by dividing them to their lengths.

You can see the plot of whole points in the below.

3 unit weight vectors in 3-D are formed by using a normal distribution. You can see the initial weights and whole data points in the plot below.

27 data points from each cluster, 81 data points are selected as training set. These points are utilized to train a winner take-all network. The weights of winner unit updated for each sample. After each epoch, cost function given in the class is calculated, when the value of this cost function becomes less than a threshold learning stops. Threshold is selected as 10.6. During learning, I observed a fluctuation in the value of cost function. To solve this problem, I decided to update the value of step length according to the following rule \(n=n*0.95^{epochcounter}\). As a result of this, n becomes smaller after each iteration.

All data points in training set are used 11 times during the training(After 11 epochs learning stops). The plot below shows the clusters and the movement of weight vectors during the training. Location of weights are shown after each epoch because it becomes too complicated when they are plotted after each update.

From the plot below, you can monitor how the total cost function changes after each epoch until learning stops.

Test

set.seed(1)

calculate_length<-function(x){
  return(sqrt(sum(x^2)))
}
n=1
no_tr_data=81
no_teest_data=9
no_input=3
no_cluster=3
#obtain training data

clus1_tr=clus1_tr/length
#clus1_tr[27,]/sqrt(sum(clus1_tr[27,]^2))
clus1_tr<-cbind(clus1_tr,2)

clus2_tr<-matrix(-rchisq(81,8),nrow=27,ncol=3)
length<-apply(clus2_tr,1,calculate_length)
clus2_tr=clus2_tr/length
clus2_tr<-cbind(clus2_tr,3)

clus3_tr<-matrix(rchisq(81,8),nrow=27,ncol=3)
clus3_tr[,1]<-clus3_tr[,1]*-1
length<-apply(clus3_tr,1,calculate_length)
clus3_tr=clus3_tr/length
clus3_tr<-cbind(clus3_tr,1)

all_clusters_training<-rbind(clus1_tr,clus2_tr)
all_clusters_training<-rbind(all_clusters_training,clus3_tr)

##learning
#initialize unit weights.
W<-matrix(rnorm(9,2,4),nrow=no_cluster)
length<-apply(W,1,calculate_length)
W=W/length

#Construct weight lists
W_list<-list(W)


train_input=all_clusters_training[,-4]
no_epoch=100
cum_error<-vector()
ep=1
decide_to_continue=TRUE
#for(ep in 1:no_epoch){
while(decide_to_continue==TRUE){
  cum_error[ep]=0
  assigned_to_which_clus<-NULL
  sample_order=sample(no_tr_data)
  for(counter in 1:no_tr_data){
    sample_index=sample_order[counter]
    inst=matrix((train_input[sample_index,]),ncol=no_input)
    h_i_matrix=W%*%t(inst)
    i_star=which(h_i_matrix==max(h_i_matrix))
    assigned_to_which_clus<-c(assigned_to_which_clus,i_star)
    update=n*(inst-W[i_star,])
    W[i_star,]=W[i_star,]+update
    #W_list[[length(W_list)+1]]<-W
  }
  #calculate total error at the end of epoch
  for(counter in 1:no_tr_data){
    sample_index=sample_order[counter]
    inst=matrix((train_input[sample_index,]),ncol=no_input)
    error=(W[assigned_to_which_clus[counter],]-inst)%*%t(W[assigned_to_which_clus[counter],]-inst)
    cum_error[ep]=cum_error[ep]+error
  }
  n=n*(0.95)^ep
  W_list[[length(W_list)+1]]<-W
  if(cum_error[length(cum_error)]<10.6){
    decide_to_continue=FALSE
  }
  ep=ep+1
}
cum_error

h_i_matrix=W%*%t(train_input)
